# Cursor Rules — notion-reporter

## Language & Runtime
- TypeScript only. No plain JS files in /src.
- Node.js 18+. Use native fetch where possible; fall back to SDK methods.
- All async functions must use async/await. No raw Promise chains.

## Architecture
- Keep API logic isolated: Notion calls live in src/notion/, Claude calls in src/claude/.
- src/index.ts only orchestrates — no API calls directly in the entry point.
- All shared types go in src/types/index.ts. No inline type declarations in logic files.

## Security
- NEVER hardcode API keys, tokens, or IDs. Always read from process.env.
- NEVER log .env values to the console, even for debugging.
- If an env var is missing at startup, throw a descriptive error and exit early.
- Do not commit .env. Remind user to fill .env.example if new vars are added.

## Error Handling
- All API calls must be wrapped in try/catch with meaningful error messages.
- If a Notion page has no block content, skip it gracefully and log a warning.
- If the Claude API call fails, output the raw structured data as fallback instead of crashing.

## Code Style
- Use named exports. No default exports except in index.ts.
- Functions should do one thing. Max 40 lines per function; extract helpers if needed.
- Use descriptive variable names. No abbreviations like `db`, `pg`, `blk`.
- Add a JSDoc comment to every exported function explaining what it does and what it returns.

## Notion API
- Always handle pagination (`has_more` + `next_cursor`) when querying the database.
- When fetching blocks, recurse into child blocks only if `has_children === true`.
- Supported block types to parse: paragraph, heading_1/2/3, bulleted_list_item,
  numbered_list_item, to_do, toggle, callout, quote. Log and skip unsupported types.

## Claude API
- Model: claude-sonnet-4-20250514
- Always send a well-structured system prompt in Portuguese.
- Include the full task data as a JSON block inside the user message.
- Keep max_tokens at 1024 for summaries.

## Output
- Terminal output should be clean and readable with section separators.
- If OUTPUT_TO_FILE=true, save to output/report-{ISO_DATE}.txt.
- Never overwrite a previous report; always use a timestamped filename.
